</p>

<p>She&rsquo;s talking about the book I wrote on how a mother might survive having a child die inside her body. Even if the grief leaves a hole forever in her belly.</p>

<p>No wonder she has lines around her eyes, Linda Barnes. It suddenly feels wrong to wipe my twat in this moment. I sit there drip-drying. In my head I go, <em>Twins. How is she even alive?</em></p>

<p>But Anna Mann is in a manic place. She&rsquo;s free, she&rsquo;s untethered from her doom, and she drives the moment somewhere else: &ldquo;Are Chris Backstrom&rsquo;s pecs scary or what? Man boobs!&rdquo;</p>

<p>We laugh. I wipe. Then Kelly Angel comes barreling in.</p>

<p>&ldquo;What are you guys doing in here?&rdquo; She shuts the door. It&rsquo;s just the three of us now, like when we were kids.</p>

<p>&ldquo;We need a picture,&rdquo; Anna says, and she whips out a point-and-shoot camera. I pull my jeans up, stand in the middle between them. Anna holds the camera at arm&rsquo;s length in front of us.</p>

<p>&ldquo;Smile!&rdquo; she laugh-yells. We do.</p>

<p>Anna shows us the result. My eyes are closed in the picture. Which happens a lot. I&rsquo;m used to it.</p>

<p>&ldquo;Oh, my God,&rdquo; Kelly says, &ldquo;look at my fat-ass arms! You have to erase that picture. Take another one.&rdquo;</p>

<p>Anna lines us up again, and again captures us trying too hard to smile. Or maybe we are smiling for real. We are laughing at least. It&rsquo;s funny: three grown women in the bathroom. I can still smell my pee.</p>

<p>This time the photo is relatively solid. I don&rsquo;t know any women who like pictures of themselves, but we don&rsquo;t look like mutants or anything. Kelly&rsquo;s arms are fine, and my eyes are open.</p>

<p>We give each other a group hug, laughing some more, and when we pull apart I see a puke-green line running down Kelly&rsquo;s face. She&rsquo;s crying, and her makeup is rivering down her cheek.</p>

<p>&ldquo;Oh, Kelly,&rdquo; Anna says, and we all pull back into a hug again. I&rsquo;m not sure what&rsquo;s happening. I feel like I missed something huge. Then, while our faces are pointed down toward the floor, Kelly says, &ldquo;Kyle .&nbsp;.&nbsp;. his Asperger&rsquo;s, he tested in the ninety-ninth percentile. As high as it gets. It&rsquo;s my fault. I waited too long to have him.&rdquo; The sentences hang there between us.</p>

<p>&ldquo;Kyle&rsquo;s the bomb!&rdquo; I blurt out before I can help it. No one says anything. Red knickers. Pickle alert. Names race through my head. Satoshi Tajiri, who designed and invented Pok&eacute;mon, has Asperger&rsquo;s. So does actress Daryl Hannah. Charles Darwin might have had it. So might Albert Einstein. Andy Warhol. Emily Dickinson. Possibly my son. And me.</p>

<p>Goddamned spectrums. Aren&rsquo;t we all on one?</p>

<p>I feel Kelly&rsquo;s arms shake. I can smell her deodorant. I pet her hair.</p>

<p>In my head I go, <em>Kelly Angel, Anna Mann, Kelly Angel, Anna Mann</em>. I can feel their shoulders in the tripartite hug. Their heads. Their hair. Kelly pats my wet butt.</p>

<p>In my head I go, <em>I should walk back and sit in the puddle of water again. I should let Kelly Angel tell her story again and again. All night</em>.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong class="large">I&rsquo;m the first person</strong> to leave the party. I hug Anna Mann and Kelly Angel hard.</p>

<p>I locate Kyle, who is back on the couch with his Mario game. I tell him good night and dump a handful of bottle caps next to him. &ldquo;In the refrigerator,&rdquo; he says, and he smiles without looking up or explaining.</p>

<p>As I walk with relief through the front door and back out into the night, Linda Barnes exits with me. &ldquo;Oh,&rdquo; I say, &ldquo;are you leaving too?&rdquo; Exit two introverts, one with a damp ass, the other with lines around her eyes.</p>

<p>&ldquo;Yeah,&rdquo; she says. Once the door is closed, she adds, &ldquo;Parties are hard for me. But it was nice to see everyone.&rdquo;</p>

<p>I know she is lying partly.</p>

<p>I remember Anna Mann telling me I should talk to Linda.</p>

<p>&ldquo;I know what happened to you,&rdquo; I say. We just stand there looking at each other, unspeakable things between our bellies.</p>

<p>Even I know this is a bizarre time and place to say that. We barely knew each other back then. Even less now.</p>

<p>In my head I go, <em>Irregular use of language</em>.</p>

<p>In my head I go, <em>Unreunion</em>.</p>

<p>She smiles. &ldquo;Thanks,&rdquo; she says, the only closure either one of us will get tonight, beyond our car doors slamming us safely shut.</p>

<p>My daughter&rsquo;s name was Lily.</p>
