			<div class="article-correspondence layout-item fill-pattern-light">
		<div class="layout-item-intro">
			<h2>Correspondence</h2>
			<a class="xsmall link-alt" href="https://www.thesunmagazine.org/letter-to-the-editor">Write a Letter to the Editor&nbsp;&#9656;</a>
		</div>

		<div id="article-correspondences" class="correspondences correspondences-collapsed">
								<div class="block-correspondence" id="501">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>I was moved to tears reading Lidia Yuknavitch&rsquo;s essay in the June 2012 issue of <em>The Sun</em> [&ldquo;<a href="/article/4670">The Unspeakable Things Between Our Bellies</a>&rdquo;]. She beautifully conveys the &ldquo;unspeakable&rdquo; private grief of a stillbirth with just the briefest reference to hers.</p>

<p>I felt as if I were at that terribly uncomfortable high-school reunion party with her and empathized with the shame and heartbreak she re-experienced. I admire how she shared her secret introspection through rhythmic repetition of the phrase &ldquo;In my head I go, .&nbsp;.&nbsp;.&rdquo;</p>

<p>There is personal writing that often seems self-indulgent to me, and then there is the superb, self-effacing writing displayed by Yuknavitch. She inspires hope through her wisdom and dignity.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">Harvey Rabichow<br>Phoenix, Arizona</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

								<div class="block-correspondence" id="477">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>I work at a very traditional men&rsquo;s barbershop, where the testosterone runs high and any hint of sensitivity is a sign of weakness. The banter is brutal sometimes. It&rsquo;s been difficult for me to adapt, but I&rsquo;ve done it, and I&rsquo;m thriving.</p>

<p>Still, I sneak little morsels of <em>The Sun</em> in at work between customers, more so on Mondays, when the other barbers are out.</p>

<p>There have been moments on Mondays when I&rsquo;ve let the tears come up and out, such as when I read Lidia Yuknavitch&rsquo;s &ldquo;<a href="/article/4670">The Unspeakable Things Between Our Bellies</a>&rdquo; [June 2012].</p>

<p>Thank you for publishing what is in some places unspeakable.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">T. Barakat<br>Oregon</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

								<div class="block-correspondence" id="465">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>I was completely taken by Lidia Yuknavitch&rsquo;s essay &ldquo;<a href="/article/4670">The Unspeakable Things between Our Bellies</a>&rdquo; [June 2012]. Her lay-it-all-out-there style fascinated me, but her last, simple line &mdash; &ldquo;My daughter&rsquo;s name was Lily&rdquo; &mdash; took my breath away. The reader knows that Yuknavitch has lost an unborn child. Then, in five words, we discover that this child is still carried by her mother.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">Bill Stoner<br>Tourves<br />France</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

					</div>

				<div class="text-center">
			<button class="b b-1 xsmall js-b-readmore-correspondence" data-collapsible="#article-correspondences" data-label="Read More Letters">Read More Letters</button>
		</div>
			</div>
    
		<div class="article-correspondence-cta">
		<div class="cta cta-l1" data-url="https://www.thesunmagazine.org/letter-to-the-editor">
			<div class="cta-intro">
				<h5 class="cta-title alt-ff">Thinking about writing us a letter?</h5>
				<p class="cta-text">Give in to the temptation. We love getting mail. <br><span class="xsmall">(Of course, we reserve the right to edit.)</span></p>
			</div>
			<a href="https://www.thesunmagazine.org/letter-to-the-editor" class="cta-button b b-4 b-padding-tight small" data-label="Write Us A Letter!">Write Us A Letter!</a>
		</div>
	</div>
	

